# BPERP — Architecture

## Deployment modes

The setup wizard offers two modes on first launch:

**Standalone (Local):** Electron forks a local Express backend; SQLite on this machine. Best for development, single-user, or testing. No NAS required.

**Network (NAS):** Backend runs on the shop NAS. Workstations are thin-client Electron apps over HTTP. SQLite lives on the NAS local disk (not a network-mounted DB file). Best for multi-workstation shops.

Both modes share the same backend and frontend code; only the backend host and DB location differ.

```
┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    Electron Main Process                       │
│  electron/main.js                                             │
│  - Window management (splash, setup, main)                    │
│  - Backend lifecycle (fork/kill) [standalone only]            │
│  - IPC handlers                                               │
│  - System tray                                                │
└─────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────┘
                      │ fork() [standalone] or HTTP [network]
┌─────────────────────▼────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    Backend (Express.js)                        │
│  backend/server.js                                            │
│  - REST API on port 3000                                      │
│  - Serves frontend static files                               │
│  - SQLite via better-sqlite3                                  │
└─────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────────┘
                      │
┌─────────────────────▼────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    Frontend (Vanilla JS)                       │
│  frontend/index.html + js/modules/                            │
│  - ES6 modules, no build step                                 │
│  - Tailwind CSS via CDN                                       │
│  - Auto-refresh for real-time data                            │
└──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                      │
         ┌────────────▼────────────┐
         │  SQLite Database File    │
         │  Local disk (standalone) │
         │  or NAS disk (network)   │
         └─────────────────────────┘
```

## SQLite considerations

- Use **better-sqlite3** (sync); not `sqlite3` (async callbacks).
- Enable WAL for concurrent reads; set busy timeout (e.g. 5000 ms) for write contention.
- WAL may not suit all network filesystems; fall back to DELETE journal if needed.
- Backups: copy the `.db` file (no pg_dump).
